  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 14-16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The casting of lots for the four chief names and the four chief aspects of gates, now proceeds. A special note is made of the care taken for the house of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Asuppim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of \"gatherings\" or \"stores.\" For all that we know of this \"house,\" we seem to be left to the verses (15, 17) of this passage, and to the expression (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), \"the storehouses, or stores of the gates\" (though the Authorized Version, the \"thresholds\" of the gates), which would have been more intelligible had it been reversed, \"the gates of the stores.\" Presumably it was a building for keeping safe certain of the sacred property, and was situated south of the temple, and, judging from ver. 17, had two doorways. The Vulgate translates ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "seniorum concilium. To Shuppim",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "seniorum concilium. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "To Shuppim",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Nothing can be made of this word in this connection, as a proper name, though we have it (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:12, 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as such. It is now generally rejected, as probably due to the error of some transcriber, whose eye may have been caught again by the last two syllables of the closely preceding \"Asuppim.\" But some would place it as the last word of the previous verse, and make it amplify the meaning of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Asuppim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"gatherings for stores.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Shallecheth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". By derivation, this word means \"sending or throwing down.\" Hence some call it, \"the refuse gate.\" The situation of it is, however, defined here, as by the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "causeway of the going up",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and would seem to render such an interpretation less likely. According to Grove (in Smith's 'Bible Dictionary'), this causeway is still traceable: it runs up from the central valley of the town to the sacred site west of the temple (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and Grove would identify the \"gate of Shallecheth\" with the present ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Bab Silsileh.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Septuagint translates ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἡ πυλὴ παστοφορίου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
